*****
[3] USA Servicemen in Germany
Date: Fri 3 Jun 2011
Source: Fox News [edited]
http://www.foxnews.com/health/2011/06/03/2-us-military-members-sickened-as-e-coli-outbreak-stabilizes-in-europe/?test=latestnews

So far, 2 USA service members based in Germany are suspected of being
victims of Europe's [EHEC] _E. coli_ outbreak Fri 3 Jun 2011, as
European authorities said the outbreak was "stabilizing."

USA military medical officers were awaiting test results from samples
taken from the ill service members, and they could be confirmed within
several days, according to Phillip Tegtmeier, a spokesman for the USA
military's Europe Regional Medical Command. "We're testing [for _E.
coli_] as a precaution," he told military newspaper Stars and Stripes
on Fri 3 Jun 2011.

One of the service members, an airman, remains in the hospital at the
Spangahlem Air Base, in western Germany. The other American reportedly
affected was treated and released while based in Heidelberg, 48 miles
south of Frankfurt.

The 2 suspected cases in US military were among some 2000 people hit
by the [EHEC] _E. coli_ outbreak across Europe, which so far claimed
18 lives, AFP reported.

Authorities said they were no closer to identifying the origin of the
outbreak Fri 3 Jun 2011, but there were signs the number of infections
was leveling out.

"The situation is that the number of new infections appears to be
stabilizing somewhat," Reinhard Brunkhorst, president of the German
Nephrology Society, told reporters in Hamburg, the epicenter of the
scare. But he added, "We are dealing here, in fact, with the biggest
epidemic caused by bacteria in recent decades." [Obviously excepting
tuberculosis & leprosy. In 2009, 2700 new cases of leprosy were
registered in one state alone -- Mato Grosso. - Mod.JW].

